---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="About">
  <article>
    <header>
      <h1>Why I Built classlesscss.com</h1>
      <p>
        By <strong
          ><a href="https://trevortylerlee.com">Trevor Tyler Lee</a></strong
        >
      </p>
    </header>

    <p>
      There are a lot of classless CSS frameworks and comparing them is
      annoying. I wanted a single page where I could flip through them all
      against the same HTML.
    </p>

    <p>
      That's what this site is. It renders a set of common HTML elements and
      lets you switch themes from a dropdown. This <code>/about</code> page exists
      so you can see how each theme handles a blog post.
    </p>

    <h2>Things You'll Notice</h2>

    <p>
      Click through the themes and you'll start to see some differences. Some
      apply a <code>max-width</code> to the body and center the content. Some have
      dark mode, some don't.
    </p>

    <h2>How It's Built</h2>

    <p>
      The site is built with <a href="https://astro.build">Astro</a>. Themes are
      loaded dynamically from their CDNs based on a query parameter. The site
      itself has no opinion on styling (except for the nav).
    </p>

    <pre><code>#nav &#123;
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 0.75rem;
  padding: 0.75rem 0;
&#125;

.nav-left &#123;
  display: flex;
  gap: 0.75rem;
  align-items: center;
&#125;

.nav-right &#123;
  display: flex;
  gap: 0.5rem;
  align-items: center;
&#125;</code></pre>

    <p>The content for this page looks like this:</p>
    <pre><code>&lt;article&gt;
  &lt;header&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Why I Built classlesscss.com&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
      By &lt;strong&gt;
        &lt;a href="https://trevortylerlee.com"&gt;Trevor Tyler Lee&lt;/a&gt;
      &lt;/strong&gt;
    &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/header&gt;

  &lt;p&gt;
    There are a lot of classless CSS frameworks and comparing them is
    annoying. I wanted a single page where I could flip through them all
    against the same HTML.
  &lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;h2&gt;Things You'll Notice&lt;/h2&gt;

  &lt;p&gt;
    Spend a few minutes clicking through themes and you'll start to see some
    differences. Some apply a &lt;code&gt;max-width&lt;/code&gt; to the body and center the
    content. Some have dark mode, some don't.
  &lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;h2&gt;How It's Built&lt;/h2&gt;

  &lt;p&gt;
    The site is built with &lt;a href="https://astro.build"&gt;Astro&lt;/a&gt;. Themes are
    loaded dynamically from their CDNs based on a query parameter. The site
    itself has no opinion on styling (except for the nav).
  &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/article&gt;</code></pre>

    <p>If you were writing in markdown, it'd look like this:</p>
    <pre><code># Why I Built classlesscss.com

By **[Trevor Tyler Lee](https://trevortylerlee.com)**

There are a lot of classless CSS frameworks and comparing them is
annoying. I wanted a single page where I could flip through them all
against the same HTML.

## Things You'll Notice

Click through the themes and you'll start to notice some
differences. Some apply a `max-width` to the body and center the
content. Some style the `&lt;nav&gt;` element, some ignore it entirely.
Some have dark mode, some don't.

## How It's Built

The site is built with [Astro](https://astro.build). Themes are
loaded dynamically from their CDNs based on a query parameter. The site
itself has no opinion on styling (except for the nav).</code></pre>

    <h2>Why are some themes starred?</h2>
    <p>
      Because they're my favorite ones so far (not affiliated). If you like that
      default HTML feel, you can check out my <a
        href="https://barebones.trevortylerlee.com"
        >open‑source Astro theme, Astro Barebones</a
      >.
    </p>
  </article>
</Layout>
